		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />The Color Dreams development kit seems kinda old and stanky.  They were reverse engineering things and didn't always guess right.<br /><s>You may consider following the coursework from Bob Rosts class on NES development<br /><!-- m --><a class="postlink" href="http://bobrost.com/nes/">http://bobrost.com/nes/</a><!-- m --><br /><br />He has this tool called nBasic which shields you from some assembly headaches.  I wouldn&#39;t called it truly BASIC though <img src="./images/smilies/icon_smile.gif" alt=":&#41;" title="Smile" /></s><br /><br />Also, if you can handle C, use NESICIDE!<br /><!-- m --><a class="postlink" href="http://www.nesicide.com/">http://www.nesicide.com/</a><!-- m --><br /><br />UPDATE:  The people who actually know what they be do have spoken!

		

		</td>
	</tr>
