		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" /><div class="quotetitle">tokumaru wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent"><div class="quotetitle">slobu wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">You may consider following the coursework from Bob Rosts class on NES development<br /><!-- m --><a class="postlink" href="http://bobrost.com/nes/">http://bobrost.com/nes/</a><!-- m --></div><br />Aren't Bob Rost's games known to have problems on hardware?</div><br /><br /><br />Yeah they run but everything is pretty much broken.  He noted about this, I think it's because of improper MMC3 scanline counter emulation.<br /><br />I read through his notes/slides when trying to program the NES for the first time.  Honestly they weren't much good for anything technical, a decent motivator that was about it.   I felt like I was able to make sense of some stuff only because I already knew a lot about the NES hardware.  I'm sure it was different sitting in his lectures, but notes(talking points outline really) and slides alone arent very useful.

		

